The art rose to incredible heights in success and afterwards in boldness of design. To prove its success I will adduce one instance, and that not of a representation of either a god or a man: our own generation saw on the Capitol, before it last went up Aa). 69. in flames burnt at the hands of the adherents of Vitellius, in the shrine of J uno, a bronze figure of a hound licking its wound, the miraculous excellence and absolute truth to life of which is shown not only by the fact of its dedication in that place but also by the method taken for insuring it3 for as no sum of money seemed to equal its value, the government enacted that its custodiaris should be answerable for its safety with their lives. (XVIII.) Of boldness of design the examples are innumerable. We see enormously huge statues devised, what are called s'olossal Colossi, as large as towers. Such is the Apollo on statues. the Capitol, brought over by Marcus Lucullus from 73 B.0. Apollonia, a city of Pontus, 45 ft. high, which cost 50012 talents to make3 or the Jupiter which the Emperor Claudius dedicated in the Campus Martius, which is dwarfed ⁶ by the proximity of the theatre of Pompey3 or the 60 ft. high statue at Taranto made by Lysippus. The remarkable thing in the case of the last is that though it can be moved by the hand, it is so nicely balanced, so it is said, that it is not dislodged from its place by any storms.
